text: Foreign Object Debris (FOD) 1 Foreign Object Debris (FOD) Introduction Foreign object debris is defined as any substance, debris, loose hardware, or article that does not belong to the item and can potentially cause damage. If foreign object debris damages a part it is called foreign object damage, and this is any impact in physical or economic terms which may or may not degrade the products safety and/or performance characteristics. Essentially anything that does not belong can be considered

FOD. FOD Consequences FOD damage is caused by Foreign Object Debris that jeopardizes quality, functionality, and/or economic value of a manufactured item. For example, a piece of FOD at the wrong place at the wrong time can: • Shred fan blades when sucked into an engine; • Blow out tires at high speeds; • Damage delicate components when trapped inside of equipment housing; • Freeze control mechanisms when lodged next to levers and handles. While hard numbers are difficult to come by, it has been

estimated that FOD costs the civilian aviation sector between $4 billion and $13 billion annually in damaged aircraft, equipment, flight delays, reduced efficiency, litigation, and other costs. FOD also has the potential to injure employees, passengers, factory workers, and others. In addition, FOD in military environments can affect national security, reducing air defense and other mission capabilities. Caution and Prevention Tool Control. A recommended practice and way to improve the FOD

Prevention Program is to identify tool locations, utilize shadow boxes, or record the tools used on a specific job and confirm that all the tools are placed back into their proper storage areas when the work is completed or at the end of each shift. Sweeping in aircraft operating areas is another method of keeping FOD under control. This can be done manually or with the airfield sweeper, which is one of the most effective pieces of equipment for removing FOD. The sweeper removes debris from

cracks and pavement joints and should be used in all areas except for those that can be Foreign Object Debris (FOD) 2 reached only with a hand broom. All aircraft operating areas, including aircraft maneuvering areas, blast fence areas, aprons, gates and the areas adjacent to them, should be swept routinely. The areas in which ground support equipment is staged should be swept periodically. Magnetic bars are another helpful way to protect against FOD. Magnetic bars can be suspended beneath tugs

and trucks to pick up metallic material. However, the bars should be cleaned regularly to prevent bars from dropping the collected debris. Vehicles driven in the aircraft operating area should be inspected periodically to ensure that they have no loose items that can fall off. Rumble strips are used often to clear areas from FOD. Driving over rumble strips can dislodge FOD from the underside of vehicles. The strips, which are between 10 ft and 15 ft long, can be moved and used at transitions

from the landside or construction areas to the aircraft operating areas. FOD containers should be placed at all gates for the collection of debris. The containers should be emptied frequently to prevent them from overflowing and becoming a source of FOD themselves. In addition, airport personnel can wear waist pouches to collect debris. Evaluating the debris collected in containers and pouches can identify its sources and indicate where personnel and equipment should be deployed for more

effective control. Other systems for preventing FOD damage include wind barriers and netting to restrict the movement of airborne FOD, fencing to prevent animals from entering the airfield, and well-maintained paved surfaces. If damaged pavement cannot be repaired immediately, aircraft should use an alternate route. Another recommendation is to identify FOD-free areas, these are places in and around your facility where maintenance, manufacturing, modification, and production of aircraft and

sub-assembly operations are conducted. Many facilities use a standard three- layered system for designating a specific work or storage area as one where FOD is of concern, which are: • Post signs, banners, decals, barriers, floor markings, tape or similar media at the entrance to a FOD-free area; • Require that personnel complete a training course before they are allowed unescorted access into the area; • Develop procedures to inventory and track parts, tools, consumables, debris and personal

items in the area. In some instances, FOD is classified as the potential failure mode and requirements of the item. Engineering may determine at what point FOD is harmful through the use of a Failure Mode and Effects Analysis also known as FMEA or a similar method in a manufacturing environment. Foreign Object Debris (FOD) 3 FOD Items A collective listing of FOD that commonly finds its way into an aircraft, aircraft component, or aircraft engine are: • Rocks, sand, loose vegetation, and

fragments of broken concrete; • Building materials; • Paper, paperclips, pens, and coins; • Aircraft hardware such as nuts, bolts, washer and cotter pins; • Sockets, screwdrivers, and other hand tools; • Metal shavings; • Broken hardware; • A persons clothing, badge, hat, keys, phone or other personal affects; • Foreign objects that are not identifiable. FOD Awareness A lack of FOD awareness and prevention may lead to significant problems with the quality or cost of delivered product and

threatens the personal safety of technicians, ground crew, pilots and passengers. The potential risks associated with FOD is a primary concern of regulators, customers and insurance companies and in an effort to mitigate occurrences a majority of airports, airlines, manufacturers and repair stations have instituted FOD Prevention Programs and also require their suppliers to establish the same to ensure every level of safety possible is being used. A FOD Prevention Program typically consists of

a: Policy – This is the broad guidelines after an analysis of all internal and external factors have been considered that can affect the goal of any FOD related incidents; Procedures – These provide detailed information and the official way to perform tasks as it relates to FOD; Checklists – These should include regimented ways to inspect tool locations, check tools into an aircraft, and 6S evaluations of the FOD program; Risk-based assessment – This permits the review, identification of risk,

and conclude the potential to cause harm to product or person; Training – An essential part of the program that teaches employees about the company’s specific Policy, Procedures, Checklists and Risk-based assessment and when and how to use each of these. By establishing and consistently following a FOD Prevention Program, occurrences and risk will decrease and quality of product and safety will increase, which equates to a big win for companies, customers, and those directly impacted by the

end-product. Foreign Object Debris (FOD) 4 Training Program Each facility is unique and performs different types of work, which is why a customized training program beyond the fundamentals of FOD training is essential should consist of the following: • Parts protection – Proper use of protection such as bags, caps, and similar are necessary to prevent unwanted entry of debris. • Material handling – Clean and well-organized workstations, carts and shelving are needed to prevent incidental

contamination. • 6S – This is a lean process improvement tool that stands for sort, straighten, shine, standardize, sustain, and safety. Following these basic principles effectively keeps your work areas FOD-free if done correctly. Always practice “Clean-as-you-go”, which is a great housekeeping technique and makes work more efficient. • Inspection – It’s always best and often required to have a second set of eyes review the work performed and also to get approval prior to closing or sealing an

item. • Tool control – Shadow boxes, tool identification numbers, tool chits, and tool logs are a few of the most common industry practices that are quite effective. • Hardware control – When removing hardware, place into bags or properly discard disposable hardware, and when using new hardware know your piece count and use magnetic trays or bags to prevent accidentally dropping into a location where it might be difficult or impossible to retrieve them. • Personal items – These are often

overlooked as a FOD threat. Employees should be instructed not to leave any personal items near aircraft or in FOD prevention areas. These items include hearing protection, vests, and kneepads. All items such as phones, tools, jackets, gloves, caps and food or beverage items that are not being worn or used should be stowed and kept away from the aircraft or products being worked on. • Reporting system – Have a way for employees to communicate near misses or incidents that have occurred is

important to a FOD program. Communication needs to be encouraged to prevent future occurrences. Plan-Do-Check-Act The Plan-Do-Check-Act or PDCA is an effective model that may be used to Draft or revise a FOD Prevention Program. Once established, follow the program by performing outlined tasks and completing checklists in a regimented order. Monitor the program and look for ways to continually improve. Setting up and watching metrics can provide valuable data to see if your company is maintaining

a certain level of quality and if improvements are necessary. Act upon the information received or observed by revising the program, which may include procedure and checklist updates, and if revisions to the program have been made, plan on providing additional training as needed on the updated material.
